{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01FXpH1C2UoNiGyW13ZCZKnq","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! codellama-34b completed (88 evals, 1831s ≈ 30 min). Final: **E2E=50.1%, ITL=0.4%**. Now llama-2-70b is optimizing. Same pattern — initial E2E=8.3% but ITL=98.9%. By eval 15, ITL down to 6.3% but E2E up to 50.6%.\n\n`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\n**E2E-ITL Tradeoff Mechanism:** The trade-off reveals a fundamental issue with BLIS's request latency decomposition. R3's CMA-ES achieved low E2E by inflating `output_token_processing_time_us` (a per-token constant) to effectively \"spread out\" request completion times, which matched real E2E but destroyed ITL accuracy. The constrained approach caps this parameter at 500μs, forcing the optimizer to find solutions that distribute latency more realistically across components. The resulting E2E degradation (~50% vs ~8%) quantifies how much of R3's E2E success was due to parameter inflation rather than genuine simulation fidelity.\n`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6c146fd0-2769-4d18-b481-0819d4602c26","uuid":"6a8c109a-8aa0-495f-94ef-99aa1114f13d"}
